{
  "answer": "**The Falsafa corpus does not contain a direct philosophical exposition by Allama Iqbal on *wahdat al-wujud* (unity of existence or being), a key doctrine in Sufi metaphysics often associated with Ibn Arabi, positing the unity of all existence in God.**\n\nIqbal's works in the corpus are limited to the Urdu poetry collection *Bang-e-Dara* (in three parts), available in English translation, original script, and transliteration.[^1] These poems reference *wahdat* (unity/oneness) poetically, portraying it as an underlying spiritual reality amid multiplicity (*kasrat*), part of India's heritage (e.g., via Guru Nanak) or nature's manifestations, but without explicit critique or positioning as in his prose works like *The Reconstruction of Religious Thought in Islam* (not in the corpus).\n\n### Poetic References to *Wahdat*:\n- In \"Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet\" (*Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 26), India is celebrated as the land \"where Nanak sang the song of oneness (*wahdat ka geet gaya*),\" linking it to Chishti's call of truth.[^2]\n- In \"Jugnu\" (*Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 27), the firefly's glow exemplifies how \"in all the Many, Unity lies deep (*kasrat mein ... wahdat ka raaz makhfi*)\"; the shine (*chamak*) is like a flower's scent (*mehak*), revealing unity hidden in diversity.[^3]\n- In *Bang-e-Dara Part 2*, Ch. 6, \"Perfect Oneness (*Kamaal-e-wahdat*) is revealed,\" tied to interconnectedness in creation.[^4]\n\nThese evoke Sufi imagery but lack Iqbal's known philosophical contrast (e.g., favoring dynamic selfhood over monistic absorption). The corpus covers 37 works, primarily Indic smṛtis, Old English poetry, French liberal theory, and select Urdu ghazals—Sufi philosophy by Iqbal is not included. For deeper analysis, consult his English prose outside this collection.",
